# ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core 8 Migration

## Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Response.End()`** — doesn't exist. It threw `ThreadAbortException` internally; .NET Core has no `Thread.Abort`.
2. **`Response.Redirect(url, true)`** — the `endResponse` parameter is gone. No more `ThreadAbortException`.
3. **`Response.Write()`** — replaced by returning `IActionResult` types.
4. **`Response.AddHeader()`** — replaced by `Response.Headers.Append()`.
5. **Web Forms event handlers** (`btnExport_Click`) — don't exist. Use action methods returning `IActionResult`.
6. **`ThreadAbortException` catch blocks** — dead code. Remove them entirely.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // File() handles Content-Disposition and streaming — no manual
        // Response.Clear/Write/End needed.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // RedirectToAction/Redirect returns a 302 — no thread abort,
            // no endResponse parameter. Code after this WILL execute
            // unless you return.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch — it cannot happen in .NET Core.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Code runs after redirect** | In Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` aborted the thread so nothing after it ran. In Core, `Redirect()` returns an `IActionResult` — you **must `return` it** or subsequent code executes silently. |
| **`Response.End()` removal** | If you call `HttpResponse.CompleteAsync()` as a substitute, it doesn't terminate execution flow. Return from the method instead. |
| **`Thread.Abort()` is gone** | `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET Core. Any code relying on `ThreadAbortException` (catch/finally patterns) must be rewritten. |
| **`Response.Write` in filters** | If middleware or filters wrote directly to `Response.Body`, switch to `IActionResult` or write to the stream explicitly with `await Response.Body.WriteAsync()`. |
| **Auth model change** | Consider `[Authorize]` attribute instead of manual `IsAuthenticated` checks — it handles redirects via middleware. |

## Cleaner Version Using `[Authorize]`

```csharp
[Authorize] // Returns 401 → auth middleware redirects to /login
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult RedirectAction()
{
    try
    {
        ProcessRequest();
        return Redirect("/success");
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        LogError(ex);
        return Redirect("/error");
    }
}
```

**One-sentence summary:** Replace imperative `Response.*` calls with declarative `IActionResult` returns, delete all `ThreadAbortException` handling, and always `return` after redirects.
